Title: Develop a Customer Order Management System to Retrieve Data Using SQL Joins

1. Aim
To understand and implement various SQL joins (INNER, LEFT, RIGHT, FULL OUTER) to retrieve combined records
from multiple related tables.

2. Objectives
● To learn the purpose and application of SQL joins.
● To retrieve data involving multiple tables using different join types.
● To understand the difference between matched and unmatched records.
● To analyze customer and order relationships using SQL.

3. Theory
3.1 What Are SQL Joins?
SQL Joins allow retrieval of data from two or more related tables using a common field (usually a primary key–foreign
key relationship).
3.2 Types of Joins
a) INNER JOIN
Returns only matching records from both tables.

Syntax:

b) LEFT JOIN (LEFT OUTER JOIN)
Returns all records from the left table and matched records from the right table.

Syntax:

c) RIGHT JOIN (RIGHT OUTER JOIN)
Returns all records from the right table and matched records from the left table.

Syntax:

d) FULL OUTER JOIN
Returns all records from both tables, matched and unmatched.

4. Tasks
1. Retrieve all customer orders using INNER JOIN.
2. Retrieve all customers including those without orders using LEFT JOIN.
3. Retrieve all orders including those with missing customer details using RIGHT JOIN.
4. Retrieve complete list of customers and orders using FULL OUTER JOIN.

5. Program / SQL
5.1 Creating Base Tables
CREATE TABLE Customer (
CustomerID INT PRIMARY KEY,
CustomerName VARCHAR(100),
Email VARCHAR(100)
);
CREATE TABLE Orders (
OrderID INT PRIMARY KEY,
CustomerID INT,
OrderDate DATE,
Amount DECIMAL(10,2),
FOREIGN KEY (CustomerID) REFERENCES Customer(CustomerID)
);

5.2 INNER JOIN

Retrieve customers who have placed orders.
SELECT
C.CustomerID, C.CustomerName,
O.OrderID, O.OrderDate, O.Amount
FROM Customer C
INNER JOIN Orders O
ON C.CustomerID = O.CustomerID;

5.3 LEFT JOIN
Retrieve all customers including those with no orders.
SELECT
C.CustomerID, C.CustomerName,
O.OrderID, O.OrderDate, O.Amount
FROM Customer C
LEFT JOIN Orders O
ON C.CustomerID = O.CustomerID;

5.4 RIGHT JOIN
Retrieve all orders, including those that have no matching customer.
SELECT
C.CustomerID, C.CustomerName,
O.OrderID, O.OrderDate, O.Amount
FROM Customer C
RIGHT JOIN Orders O
ON C.CustomerID = O.CustomerID;

5.5 FULL OUTER JOIN
Retrieve all data, whether matched or unmatched.
Note:MySQL does not support FULL OUTER JOIN directly; we use UNION.
SELECT
C.CustomerID, C.CustomerName,
O.OrderID, O.OrderDate, O.Amount
FROM Customer C

LEFT JOIN Orders O
ON C.CustomerID = O.CustomerID
UNION
SELECT
C.CustomerID, C.CustomerName,
O.OrderID, O.OrderDate, O.Amount
FROM Customer C
RIGHT JOIN Orders O
ON C.CustomerID = O.CustomerID;

6. Output
● Successfully retrieved order details using INNER JOIN.
● Retrieved all customers irrespective of order status using LEFT JOIN.
● Retrieved all orders including unmatched records using RIGHT JOIN.
● Displayed complete combined records using FULL OUTER JOIN.
7. Conclusion
This experiment demonstrated the practical usage of SQL joins to retrieve related records from multiple tables. It
enhanced understanding of combining data using INNER, LEFT, RIGHT, and FULL OUTER JOIN operations.
